        <h2>Work Permit Strategies for ELSS</h2>
        <p>
          Getting and maintaining your work permit is critical for ELSS success. Here are common pathways:
        </p>

        <h3>LMIA-Based Work Permits</h3>
        <p>
          Most ELSS applicants arrive on LMIA-based work permits. Your employer must:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Demonstrate they couldn't find Canadian workers</li>
          <li>Pay the $1,000 LMIA processing fee</li>
          <li>Offer wages at or above the median for the occupation</li>
          <li>Provide documentation of recruitment efforts</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Working Holiday Visa (IEC)</h3>
        <p>
          If you're from an IEC-eligible country (UK, Australia, France, Germany, etc.), you may start on a working holiday visa and transition to LMIA-based permit for ELSS. Key considerations:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Working holiday time counts toward your 9 months</li>
          <li>You'll need to switch to LMIA permit before holiday visa expires</li>
          <li>Plan the transition early‚ÄîLMIA processing takes 2-4 months</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Post-ELSS Work Authorization</h3>
        <p>
          Unlike Express Entry BC applicants, ELSS nominees are <strong>not eligible for Bridging Open Work Permits (BOWP)</strong>. You must maintain valid work authorization through:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>LMIA-based work permit extensions</li>
          <li>Implied status (if extension submitted before expiry)</li>
          <li>Continued employment with same employer</li>
        </ul>

